{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}
{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}
The '''Bilsæte''' ("dwellers of the ridge") were a tribe or clan in [[Anglo-Saxon]] England living in an area surrounding a small ridge now occupied by the modern settlement of [[Bilston]] in the [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]] of [[England]].

A grant of land from [[King Aethelred]] bestowing Wolverhampton on Lady [[Wulfrun]] in 985 named the settlement as ''Bilsatena'',<ref>[http://www.anglo-saxons.net/hwaet/?do=get&type=charter&id=860 ''Charter S 860'']</ref> and a later [[Anglo-Saxon charters|Anglo-Saxon charter]] of 996 calls the settlement ''Bilsetnatun''.<ref>[http://www.anglo-saxons.net/hwaet/?do=get&id=1380&type=charter ''Charter S 1380'']</ref> These names confirm the etymology (dwelling (''tun'') of the people (''saetna'') of the ridge (''bil''),<ref name=Johnston>Johnston, James B. (1915) ''The Place-Names of England and Wales''. London: John Murray</ref> and disproves the alternative and better known etymology for Bilston (''Billestun'').

