{{coord|49|36|43|N|06|07|59|E|display=title}} [[File:Luxembourg city 2007 05.JPG|thumb|Exterior of the museum, seen in 2007]] The '''National Museum of History and Art''' ({{lang-lb|Nationalmusée fir Geschicht a Konscht}}, {{lang-fr|Musée national d'histoire et d'art}}, {{lang-de|Nationalmuseum für Geschichte und Kunst}}), abbreviated to '''MNHA''', is a [[museum]] located in [[Luxembourg City]], in southern [[Luxembourg]]. It is dedicated to displaying [[Work of art|artwork]]s and [[Artifact (archaeology)|artefact]]s from all epochs of [[History of Luxembourg|Luxembourg history]]. The museum is situated in [[Fishmarket]], the historic heart of the city, in the [[Ville Haute]] [[Quarters of Luxembourg City|quarter]].
==History== [[File:Luxembourg MNHA 261 Epona Dalheim.jpg|thumb|150px|A Roman carving from Dalheim in the museum]] [[File:Lang Barrage 1913.jpg|thumb|''[[The Dam]]'', 1913, by [[Dominique Lang]], is held in the museums collection]] The first proposal for such a museum was made during the [[French First Republic|French]] occupation of the [[French Revolutionary Wars|Revolutionary Wars]], when Luxembourg was annexed into the [[Départements of France|département]] of [[Forêts]]. However, the museum was never opened, despite the expropriation of a number of artefacts from the church.<ref name="Historique">{{cite web |url=http://www.mnha.public.lu/musee/historique/index.html |title=Historique |accessdate=2007-01-02 |work= |publisher=Musée national d'histoire et d'art |language=fr |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070219102800/http://www.mnha.public.lu/musee/historique/index.html |archivedate=2007-02-19 |df= }}</ref>
With the affirmation of Luxembourg's independence under the [[Treaty of London, 1839|1839 Treaty of London]] came a greater interest by native Luxembourgers in promoting the history of their country. In 1845, historians and archaeologists formed the 'Society for the Study and Preservation of Historic Monuments in the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg' ({{lang-fr|Société pour la recherche et la conservation des monuments historiques dans le Grand-Duché de Luxembourg}}), regularly known as the 'Archaeological Society' ({{lang-fr|Société archéologique}}).<ref name="Historique" /> The society took over the responsibility of maintaining a collection of historic antiquities from Luxembourg City's [[wikt:athenaeum|Athenaeum]].
In 1868, the Society received a boost from the establishment of the [[Royal-Grand Ducal Institute]] ({{lang-fr|Institut royal grand-ducal}}),<ref>To become just the 'Grand Ducal Institute' ({{lang-fr|Institut Grand-Ducal}}) in 1890, when the [[personal union]] of Luxembourg and the [[Netherlands]] ended.</ref> amongst the responsibilities of which was the conservation of archaeological collections.<ref name="Historique" />
The museum has been expanded with a new building designed by Christian Bauer et Associés, opened in 2002.<ref>[http://www.mnha.public.lu/musee/restructuration/index.html National Museum of History and Art: Restructuration], retrieved 25 March 2010 {{fr icon}}</ref> <!--Expansion to present day-->
