'''Rowland Parker''' (1912 - 1989) was an author and [[Social history|social historian]]. His 1975 work, ''The Common Stream,'' has achieved recognition as a classic of social history.<ref>{{cite web|title=C is for the Common Stream|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/10673706/The-Alphabet-Library-C-is-for-The-Common-Stream-by-Rowland-Parker.html|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Jenkins|first1=Simon|title=Thatcher and sons: a revolution in three acts|date=2007|publisher=Penguin|location=London|isbn=978-0141006246|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=C1sL7-Wm8q0C&pg=PT462&lpg=PT462&dq=rowland+parker+common+stream+classic&source=bl&ots=JrGH0Jc8ak&sig=jWwMFjRkyEyJ1y1U9HXE_gi6Tnc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiykZXTrJHPAhXWFsAKHU41Cbk4ChDoAQgwMAg#v=onepage&q=rowland%20parker%20common%20stream%20classic&f=false|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Common Stream|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/rowland-parker/the-common-stream-portrait-of-an-english-villag/|website=Kirkus Reviews}}</ref>
Parker was born in 1912 in [[North Lincolnshire]]. His father, grandfather and great-grandfather were all farmers and his youth was spent in the country. He was educated at [[Louth Grammar School]], won a scholarship to the [[University of Nottingham]] and then trained as a teacher. In 1935 he joined the staff of what was then the Central School, Cambridge, and, except for the war, remained there until his retirement in 1972. He enlisted in the [[Royal Artillery]] in 1940, serving in [[North Africa]], [[Italy]], [[Egypt]], [[Syria]] and [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], where he began to take an interest in [[archaeology]] and history.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Common Stream|url=http://www.travelbooks.co.uk/shop-online-books/common-stream-rowland-parker|website=Eland Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Common Stream|url=http://www.gleebooks.com.au/_blog/2nd-hand-rows/post/the-common-stream/|website=Glee books}}</ref> After the war, he moved to [[Foxton, Cambridgeshire|Foxton]], and remained there until his death in 1989.<ref name="daughter">{{cite web|title=Oct 2011 Meeting Report|url=http://www.sawstonhistory.org.uk/oct-2011-meeting-report.htm|website=Sawston Village History Society|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref> He became known as a notable local figure after ''The Common Stream'' increased the village's national profile.<ref>{{cite web|title=Notable Foxtonians|url=http://www.commonstream.co.uk/notable-foxtonians-rowland-parker/|website=The Common Stream}}</ref>
==Works== *''Cottage on the Green'' (1973) *''The Common Stream'' (1975; new edition by [[Eland Books|Eland]] in 2015) *''On the Road: The Papworth Story'' (1977)<ref>See [[Papworth Industries]].</ref> *''Men of Dunwich: The story of a vanished town'' (1979) *''Town and Gown: Seven hundred years' war in Cambridge'' (1983)
